<HEADLINE>
<P>
PREGNANCY DIABETES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. NEIL SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: If a woman is found to have diabetes when she becomes pregnant for 
the first time, does that mean she'll probably have the same problem each time 
she becomes pregnant? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: It is estimated that about one-third of women who develop diabetes 
during one pregnancy will not have a recurrence during a subsequent pregnancy. 
</P>
<P>
Some of the reasons suggested to explain this are changes in diet, exercise 
habits, the degree of stress they may be subjected to and other life-style 
factors that may affect diabetes. 
</P>
<P>
Women who develop diabetes during one pregnancy as well as during a subsequent 
pregnancy are more likely to be heavier than women who don't. 
</P>
<P>
For Perry, Princeton, N.J.: Basketball players should trim their fingernails 
before a game. This would reduce the risk of corneal abrasions, which are quite 
common. 
</P>
</TEXT>
