</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WARSAW 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Eritrean rebels attacked and crippled a Polish freighter off the Ethiopian 
coast and captured 29 crew members and a passenger, the Polish government said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
"We have heard that the crew is safe and in the care of the Eritrean Liberation 
Front," government spokesman Stefan Staniszewski said at a Warsaw news 
conference. 
</P>
<P>
Staniszewski said the Eritreans admitted their guerrillas attacked the vessel 
Jan. 3 and that the 29 crew members and a woman passenger, identified by Polish 
newspapers as the wife of a crewman, were captured. 
</P>
<P>
Staniszewski said the 11,627-ton vessel, Boleslaw Krzywousty, was found ablaze, 
unmanned and apparently aground Jan. 4 off the Ethiopian coast by the Polish 
ship Asnyk, which was alerted by distress signals. 
</P>
