<P>
FUJITSU TOUTS FASTER COMPUTER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TOKYO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Fujitsu Ltd. said today it has developed a "super neural computer" with 
processing speeds several hundred times faster than that of models on the 
market. 
</P>
<P>
A prototype built by Fujitsu Laboratories links 256 digital signal processors 
in parallel to achieve processing speeds of 500 million connection updates per 
second, a company spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
This is several hundred times faster than models sold by U.S. companies and 
about 2,000 times quicker than neural network simulations run on engineering 
workstations, he said. 
</P>
<P>
Neural networks simulate the workings of the brain, which through its network 
of interconnected neurons and synapses is capable of processing tremendous 
quantities of data and performing many tasks simultaneously. 
</P>
<P>
No date has been set for commercializing the Fujitsu system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
