<P>
SOVIETS DEFEND TRADE ALLIANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MOSCOW 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Parts of Comecon are obsolete and need radical changes, but the Soviet Union 
opposes disbanding the East Bloc trade alliance as some nations have suggested, 
a Soviet spokesman said today. 
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov indicated what the Soviet 
response will be to appeals by Hungary, Czechoslovakia and Poland for a major 
overhaul of Comecon when it meets Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
Gerasimov blamed poor implementation of good past decisions for many of 
Comecon's woes. 
</P>
<P>
"There is no dynamism. There is no sign of improvement in the trade structure. 
There is no technological progress," he said. "And so we believe there must be 
radical measures to restructure the mechanism of cooperation." 
</P>
<P>
But, he added, "As far as the direct answer to whether we need Comecon or not, 
yes, we need it," Gerasimov said. 
</P>
<P>
Czechoslovak Finance Minister Vaclav Klaus said Thursday there was no reason 
for Comecon to exist. 
</P>
</TEXT>
