'AUNT BEE' LEAVES ESTATE TO HOSPITAL, PUBLIC TELEVISION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SILER CITY, N.C. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The woman who portrayed the kindly Aunt Bee on television's "The Andy Griffith 
Show" left her house to the town hospital and its contents to a center for 
public television, an attorney said. 
</P>
<P>
"Anybody who reads the will can see that she remembered those who remembered 
her at the last moments," attorney Sam Williams said about how Frances Bavier 
divided her $700,000 estate. 
</P>
<P>
The huge brick-and-stone house, where Bavier died in her sleep at 86 on Dec. 6, 
was bequeathed to Moore Memorial Hospital in Pinehurst, where the actress was 
treated several times. 
</P>
<P>
The contents of the house were donated to the University of North Carolina 
Center for Public Television, he said. 
